1. Box plot

  • Draw boxplot using PlantGrowth dataset.
  • x axis represents group, y axis represents weight.
  • Use geom_boxplot() function to draw boxplot.
  • Use labs() function to add title, axis labels, and caption.
  • Use theme() function to center the title.
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=20))

2. Swap X and Y axes

  • Use coord_flip() function to swap x and y axes.
ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = 'Weight vs Group', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=20))

3. Arrange two plots side by side

  • Install gridExtra library.
  • Prepare two plots: p1, p2.
  • Use grid.arrange() function to arrange plots and add title.
library(gridExtra)

p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=20))

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = 'Weight vs Group', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=20))

# Add title
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Swap X and Y axes')

4. Setting the Range of a Continuous Axis

p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ylim(0, max(PlantGrowth$weight)) +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Add title
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Setting the Range of a Continuous Axis')

5. Reversing a Continuous Axis

p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

p3 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  ylim(6.5, 3.5) +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By James, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
Scale for y is already present.
Adding another scale for y, which will replace the existing scale.
# Add title
grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3,
             top = 'Reversing a Continuous Axis')

9. Removing Tick Marks and Labels

p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot()

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank())

p3 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank())

p4 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = NULL)

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, ncol = 4,
             top = 'Removing Tick Marks and Labels')

10. Changing the Text of Tick Labels

12. Changing the Appearance of Tick Labels

pg_plot <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(
    breaks = c("ctrl", "trt1", "trt2"),
    labels = c("Control", "Treatment 1", "Treatment 2")
  )
p1 <- pg_plot
p2 <- pg_plot +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = .5))
p3 <- pg_plot +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3,
             top = 'Changing the Appearance of Tick Labels')

19. Rotate the labels on x axis

library(dplyr)

Attaching package: 'dplyr'
The following object is masked from 'package:MASS':

    select
The following object is masked from 'package:gridExtra':

    combine
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
# Take a subset of economics
econ_mod <- economics %>%
  filter(date >= as.Date("1992-05-01") & date <  as.Date("1993-06-01"))

# Create the base plot, which does not specify the breaks
p1 <- ggplot(econ_mod, aes(x = date, y = psavert)) +
  geom_line()

# Specify breaks as a Date vector
datebreaks <- seq(as.Date("1992-06-01"), as.Date("1993-06-01"), by = "2 month")

# Use breaks, and rotate text labels
p2 <- p1 +
  scale_x_date(breaks = datebreaks) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))

grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 2,
             top = 'Rotate the labels on x axis')

20. Using Relative Times on an Axis

# Convert WWWusage time-series object to data frame
www <- data.frame(
  minute = as.numeric(time(WWWusage)),
  users  = as.numeric(WWWusage)
)

# Define a formatter function - converts time in minutes to a string
timeHM_formatter <- function(x) {
  h <- floor(x/60)
  m <- floor(x %% 60)
  lab <- sprintf("%d:%02d", h, m) # Format the strings as HH:MM
  return(lab)
}
# Default x axis
p1 <- ggplot(www, aes(x = minute, y = users)) +
  geom_line()

# With formatted times
p2 <- ggplot(www, aes(x = minute, y = users)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "time",
    breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 10),
    labels = timeHM_formatter
  )
grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 2,
             top = 'Using Relative Times on an Axis')
